<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian Delegation Departs for Geneva Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian Delegation Departs for Geneva Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405103794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1003 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 24 May (TANJUG) -- A delegation of the 
republic of Srpska -- made up of Momcilo Krajisnik, president of 
the republic of Srpska people's assembly, and foreign minister 
Aleksa Buha -- left for Geneva today where a meeting between the 
contact group and the cochairmen of the conference on the former 
Yugoslavia, David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, is being held. 
  The republic of Srpska's press office has announced that the 
delegation is to present to representatives of the international 
community and cochairmen Owen and Stoltenberg the Serb side's 
stance on the possible resumption of the peace talks, stressing 
the establishment of a lasting cease-fire in all parts of that 
former Yugoslav republic and the equal treatment of all sides in 
the conflict. This is in line with the conclusions of the 
republic of Srpska assembly adopted at a recent session in Brcko. 
  The Serbian side will warn of the Muslim offensive that has 
been going on with unabated intensity, and will insist that the 
unfair and inadequate behavior of the Muslim side hampers any 
resumption of talks, a statement says. The republic of Srpska's 
delegation is expected to take part in consultative meetings 
with important personalities from the international community 
who are interested in the speedy creation of conditions 
necessary for the resumption of talks. 
  Immediately before departure, Krajisnik said that there were 
considerable problems in creating conditions for the resumption 
of talks. The statement stresses that the contact group for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina has ignored the solving of these problems, 
underestimating their importance. 

</TEXT>

