<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec Comments on Sudeten German Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zieleniec Comments on Sudeten German Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405094194 Prague CTK in English 1206 GMT 23 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2405094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 23 (CTK) -- Czech Foreign Minister 
Josef Zieleniec said today he viewed the fact that two groups of 
demonstrators at the opening of the 45th Sudeten German congress 
unfolded banners reading "No to the Munich Treaty" and "Cheb 
Must Remain Czech" as an important sign of German citizens 
beginning to think a little but about the demands by the Sudeten 
German Landmsannschaft (SL). The congress was held in Nuremberg 
last weekend. Cheb is a west Bohemian district town situated 
near the Czech-German border. 
  "I believe this is a significant moment," Zieleniec told 
journalists. "I hope that German political circles will think so 
as well, since thinking about the future is the basis of mutual 
reconciliation," he added. 
  Zieleniec pointed out that the SL demands were the demands 
for a revision of the results of World War Two, with all 
consequences following from it. In this connection, he warned 
against the danger of an avalanche, "which can extend to very 
unpredictable and distant ends". 
  Zieleniec said he considered the demands voiced at the 
congress for the abolition of the Benes decrees (on the 
displacement of Sudeten Germans from Czechoslovakia after World 
War Two) to be standard demands articulated for long, with 
"differing extents of vehemence" by individual Sudeten German 
politicians. No considerable deviation from this trend was 
recorded at the Sudeten German congress, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

