<H3> <TI>   Poll: Trade Minister Most Popular Politician </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll: Trade Minister Most Popular Politician </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2305133694 Prague CTK in English 1154 GMT 23 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2305133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 23 (CTK) -- Trade and Industry Minister 
Vladimir Dlouhy (ODA, Civic Democratic Alliance) is with 87 per 
cent the most popular Czech politician, a poll conducted by the 
Centre of Empiric Researches (STEM) in early May revealed. 
Dlouhy is followed by Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec (ODS, 
Civic Democratic Party) with 72 per cent, former Foreign 
Minister Jiri Dienstbier (Free Democrats) with 70 per cent, 
Premier Vaclav Klaus (ODS) with 68 per cent and Deputy Premier 
Jan Kalvoda (ODA) with 67 per cent. 
  The question "do you trust President Vaclav Havel" was 
answered in the affirmative by 66 per cent of those surveyed. 
Sixty-two per cent of Czechs believe the government is working 
well, while the figure for the parliament is 37 per cent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55920 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu101__a94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-101-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opinion Poll Shows Decline in ODS Popularity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opinion Poll Shows Decline in ODS Popularity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405095994 Prague CTK in English 1236 GMT 23 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2405095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 23 (CTK) -- For the first time in the 
past twelve months the popularity of the ODS (Civic Democratic 
Party) dropped under 30 percent, to 29 percent, a poll conducted 
by the Center of the Empiric Researches (STEM) in early May 
revealed. 
  Last May 36 percent of those surveyed would have voted for 
the ODS. On the other hand, the polls of the ODA (Civic 
Democratic Alliance) are steadily increasing from 10 percent a 
year ago to the present 14.8 percent. The ODA is followed by 
the Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD) with 14.2 percent, and 
the Left Bloc, the Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM) 
and Democratic Left Party (SDL) with a total of 11.5 percent. 
  Parties under the 5-percent limit necessary to get to the 
parliament would receive 4.1 percent (Christian Democratic 
Union- Czechoslovak People's Party, KDU-CSL), 4 percent 
(Assembly for the Republic-Czechoslovak Republican Party, 
SPR-RSC) and one to two percent (Bohemian and Moravian Center 
Party, Green Party, Christian Democratic Party, and Liberal 
Social Union). 
  The voter turn-out would be 64 percent, while 23 percent 
have 
not made up their mind, and 12 percent are decided not to take 
part, the poll found. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

