<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Delegation's Visit to Israel Assessed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Delegation's Visit to Israel Assessed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2205193794 Prague CTK in English 1907 GMT 22 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2205193794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tel Aviv, May 22 (CTK) -- The visit by a delegation 
from the Czech Defence Ministry to Israel has opened up 
possibilities for closer cooperation between the ministries and 
armies of the two countries, and has created a framework for 
specific cooperation between Czech and Israeli companies in 
weapons modernisation, Defence Minister Antonin Baudys said 
today. 
  The five-day visit has seen the signing of an outline 
memorandum on military cooperation. The Czech delegation was 
familiarised with the structure, management and organisation of 
the Israeli army, saw soldiers training and carried on a number 
of negotiations with both state and private military industry 
companies. 
  Baudys said Israel had a very good quality, highly-organised 
and well-trained army, and that Israeli weapons companies were 
offering the Czechs what they needed -- top level technology for 
modernising the weapons and weapons systems used up till now. 
Modernisation programmes would bring new jobs and would later 
allow Czech companies to break into the world market, Baudys 
said. 
  He stressed that no specific agreements had been signed in 
Israel, and that cooperation in the near future would be the 
subject of negotiations between companies. 
  Oskar Sima, director of a military repair company, told CTK 
that one of the very attractive offers which had been made to 
his company was technology for the modernisation of T-72 Soviet 
tanks. An agreement on the supply of the technology was to be 
signed at the end of May, Sima said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55922 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu101__a94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-101-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interest in Cooperation Stressed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interest in Cooperation Stressed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2305130194 Prague CTK in English 1117 GMT 23 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2305130194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 23 (CTK) -- Israeli arms manufacturers 
are among serious candidates for cooperation with Czech 
companies in the modernisation of the Czech military technology, 
Defence Minister Antonin Baudys, who returned yesterday from a 
five-day visit to Israel, told CTK today. 
  The Czech Army is facing a complex transformation process 
which involves modernisation of the obsolete military equipment. 
This should be performed by Czech companies cooperating with 
foreign suppliers, Baudys said during a discussion-meeting with 
CTK editors. For this, the Czech companies have sufficient 
potential but they are lacking sophisticated know-how which is 
being offered by Israel, he added. 
  The Israeli army has rich experience with modernising the 
Soviet-made weapons and weapons systems of which it gained a 
considerable amount after the Arab-Israeli 1967 Six-Day War, 
Baudys said. 
  The Israeli companies are offering top-quality technology 
for 
modernising the Slovak-made T-72 tanks, MiG aircraft, missile 
systems and sophisticated ammunition. 
  The individual companies will make the final decision after 
the Defence Ministry presents concrete orders, said Baudys, 
adding that the projects of modernisation of the Czech Army 
would be completed by the end of June. 
  The visit of the Czech Defence Ministry delegation to Israel 
during which the two countries signed an outline memorandum on 
military cooperation paved the way for cooperation in the 
military sphere, Baudys said. Israel considers the Czech 
Republic a reliable and trustworthy partner which is evidenced 
by the fact that cooperation in such a delicate sphere as 
military technology usable for civilian purposes as well was 
supported by the Israeli Defence Ministry and Yitzhak Rabin, 
Israeli premier and defence minister, Baudys stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

