<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Free Democrat Comments on Coalition Prospects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Free Democrat Comments on Coalition Prospects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405094394 Budapest MTI in English 1931 GMT 20 May 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2405094394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 20 May (MTI) -- Coalition or a one-party 
government is what is at issue on May 29, round two of national 
elections, Gabor Kuncze, prime minister candidate of the 
Alliance of Free Democrats (SZDSZ), said in Pecs, southern 
Hungary, today. 
  For the Free Democrats, it will decide if they enjoy enough 
support to implement their programme, he said. 
  Should the Hungarian Socialist Party (MSZP) win an outright 
majority in parliament, there are minimal chances of a 
MSZP-SZDSZ coalition being formed, Kuncze said, adding that a 
final decision would be up to the SZDSZ delegates' assembly on 
June 5. 
  If the Socialists won more than 50 percent of mandates, the 
SZDSZ would have no genuine weight in any coalition, Kuncze told 
MTI, saying the Free Democrats are not willing to be coalition 
"extras". 
  If the MSZP won less than 50 percent and the SZDSZ won about 
25 per cent of mandates, the Free Democrats could have a genuine 
influence on government, Kuncze said. 

</TEXT>

