</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa Visit to Switzerland Previewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa Visit to Switzerland Previewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405124594 Warsaw PAP in English 1214 GMT 24 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2405124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 24 -- President Lech Walesa is setting 
off for a three-day visit to Switzerland on Wednesday, at the 
invitation of Swiss President Otto Stich on behalf of the 
Federal Council of the Swiss Confederation. 
  Switzerland plays host only once a year to an official 
visitor from a foreign state. Poland is the first country in 
Central and Eastern Europe to have received an invitation for 
such a visit. 
  President Walesa will head a delegation including Foreign 
Minister Andrzej Olechowski, head of the president's chancellery 
Janusz Ziolkowski, National Bank of Poland President Hanna 
Gronkiewicz-Waltz and Deputy Finance Minister Henryk Chmielak. 
  Lech Walesa will also be accompanied by 15 representatives 
of 
Polish business since the visit is intended to strengthen 
Polish- Swiss economic ties. At the moment Switzerland is in 
13th place in the league of Poland's trading partners, and 234 
Swiss firms operate in Poland with a small capital of 170 
million dollars. 
  The last significant Polish-Swiss business deal was the 
purchase of the Poznan firm "Goplana" by Nestle. 
  No trade agreements are intended to be signed but several 
meetings are planned which should bear fruit later on. Among 
these is a "round table" meeting planned with representatives of 
Swiss economic circles which will be chaired by the presidents 
of both countries. 
  The Polish delegation has plans to visit four Swiss cantons 
-- Berne, Zurich, St. Gallen and Solure (which is represented by 
the Swiss president). President Walesa is to meet 
representatives of the thousands-strong Polish community. 
  This will be Walesa's first visit to Switzerland in his 
capacity as Polish president. But in June 1981 as leader of 
Solidarity he headed a delegation to the International Labour 
Organisation in Geneva. 
  Bronislaw Geremek, who is now one of the leaders of the 
Freedom Union, accompanied him at the time. Several meetings 
took place then. This was one of the elements of the "existence 
of Poland in the world up to the achieving of independence," 
presidential press spokesman Andrzej Drzycimski said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

