<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Proposals Referred to Committee </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Armed Forces Proposals Referred to Committee </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405130694 Warsaw PAP in English 1241 GMT 24 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2405130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 24 -- After a twelve-minute long session 
attended by President Lech Walesa, the cabinet Tuesday decided 
to approve of his proposal and pass on a document outlining 
major changes in the organization of the Polish Armed Forces to 
the National Defence Committee (KOK). 
  Walesa told reporters after the session that he had asked 
the 
prime minister and the cabinet to transfer discussion on topics 
that "are very important and must not breed conflicts between 
us" to the KOK forum. 
  The president also described the topics contained in the 
document, drafted by the National Defence Ministry, as delicate 
and requiring in-depth discussion. 
  Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak noted that KOK members 
include 
the Sejm and Senate speakers, along top representatives of the 
executive branch. 
  According to Defence Minister Piotr Kolodziejczyk, the 
document was very mature and there was no need for changes in 
it. He also said that the document concerned very important 
matters and its final elaboration should not be done under the 
pressure of time. Kolodziejczyk acknowledged the right of the 
KOK to deal with the matter. 
  The document provides for the establishment of command 
centres for the Army, the Navy and the Air Force. The joint 
commander of all three kinds of Armed Forces would report to the 
minister of defence. An earlier version of the proposal 
envisaged that he would report directly to the president. 

</TEXT>

