<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Views Stability Pact, Border Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik Views Stability Pact, Border Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005163594 Prague CTK in English 1248 GMT 20 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2005163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava May 20 (CTK) -- If the Stability Pact 
guarantees existing borders, space will be created for the 
inclusion of this document in a Slovak-Hungarian basic treaty, 
Slovak Premier Jozef Moravcik said today. 
  The conclusion of the Stability Pact between the European 
Union (EU) and Central and East European countries is primarily 
aimed at solving ethnic minority problems as well as the border 
issues between some states, he said. He said that though the 
current working shape of the document is acceptable to Slovakia, 
certain changes could be expected at the Paris conference 
scheduled for next week as some states voiced certain 
reservations against it. 
  "The inclusion of the passage on the inviolability of the 
existing Slovak-Hungarian border in the basic treaty was 
proposed by Slovakia," Moravcik said. He said that Slovak 
diplomats proceeded from the fact that during the discussion on 
a similar treaty with Ukraine certain reservations were raised. 
  The guarantees for the joint border, about which the 
Hungarian side is "reserved", is a sensitive problem for 
Slovakia. "We have to unambiguously and consistently reject the 
fear of irredentism in Slovakia," he said, adding that the 
guarantee of borders have been and are part of international 
documents. 
  "We have come to believe that EU participation in the 
formulation of a Slovak-Hungarian treaty would not necessarily 
to bring positive results," Moravcik said asked why Slovakia 
refused to conclude a treaty with Hungary under EU supervision. 
"There is no reason for such treaties to be agreed upon under 
the auspices of third countries," he added. 
  He pointed out, however, that the Stability Pact could 
provide necessary guarantees for its member states and create 
the necessary conditions for the "gradual integration" of nine 
Central and East European countries into the EU. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

