<F P=103> AU2405101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, May 23 (CTK) -- The Christian Democrats 
(KDH) will answer the invitation of two smaller parties, the 
Democratic Party (DS) and the Party of Entrepreneurs and 
Tradespeople (SPZ) to form an electoral coalition at Wednesday's 
meeting of right-wing parties, KDH chairman Jan Carnogursky told 
CTK today. 
  "We do not yet have a special standpoint on this invitation. 
We are still maintaining our offer of open candidate sheets," 
Carnogursky said. He confirmed that rather than form an 
electoral coalition, the KDH preferred to continue offering 
places on its candidate lists to politicians from the smaller 
right-wing parties. 
  The KDH's offer has as yet been accepted only by politicians 
known from the days of the Czechoslovak federation, headed by 
ex- Minister of the Interior Jan Langos. While the Slovak left 
today officially entered into a coalition, the other side of the 
political spectrum is still unclear. According to pre-electoral 
polls, only the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), the 
left-wing coalition and the KDH are sure of gaining the five per 
cent of votes needed to enter parliament. 
  In the 1992 elections the Slovak right was not able to 
overcome its fragmented nature. The method in which the 
right-wing parties will enter the autumn elections has to be 
decided before the candidate lists close in July. 

</TEXT>

