<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik Sets Conditions for Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajisnik Sets Conditions for Peace Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405202294 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2405202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Borko Stosic from Geneva] </F>
  [Text] The Serbian delegation arrived in Geneva this 
afternoon. Immediately upon their arrival from the airport, 
President Krajisnik [title as heard] and Foreign Minister Aleksa 
Buha left for the Russian Permanent Mission to the United 
Nations where they sat down with the member of the contact group 
representing Russia. They stayed there for nearly two hours and 
afterward went directly to the Palace of Nations to meet with 
Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg. This meeting lasted for 
quite some time. 
  At approximately 1700, after the meeting, Momcilo Krajisnik 
gave a brief statement for the press in which he stressed that 
the Serbian Republic delegation will participate in the talks on 
three conditions: 
  That it be given a perfectly equal status; 
  That all hostilities end immediately; 
  That the percentages regarding the division of territories 
be 
a subject of discussion and negotiations and not determined in 
advance by a dictate. Namely, if this is the case then there is 
no reason for the talks. 
  Regarding [President of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency] 
Alija Izetbegovic, he is repeating his stance that he had not 
arrived to negotiate but to merely inform himself and establish 
contacts with the representatives of the United States and 
Russia in the contact group. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

