<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Austrian's Remarks on Sudeten Germans Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Austrian's Remarks on Sudeten Germans Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405114394 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 24 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU2405114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [DIE PRESSE report: "Charles IV Prize: Prague Warns and </F>
Placates"] 
  [Text] Nuremberg/Krumlov -- On the occasion of the 
awarding of the "European Charles IV Prize" of the Sudeten 
German Landsmannschaft in Nuremberg at Whitsun weekend, Foreign 
Minister Alois Mock said that the expulsion of the Sudeten 
Germans after World War II was "one of the major unlawful acts" 
of the 20th century. However, Mock also recalled that the 
crimes of the National Socialists had preceded the forcible 
resettlement. 
  In Krumov, Prague's Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec told 
Austrian journalists that Mock's comments in connection with the 
awarding of the Charles IV Prize "might burden bilateral 
relations." "However, the whole affair should not be 
overestimated either." 

</TEXT>

