<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Accepts Principles of Bosnia Mediators </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman Accepts Principles of Bosnia Mediators </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405211294 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2000 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405211294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Croatian President Dr. Franjo Tudjman received in 
the Presidential Palace this evening a delegation of countries 
whose diplomatic envoys make up the contact group for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. French Ambassador Henri Marie-Chenu, British 
Ambassador Brian Sparrow, Belgian Ambassador Frans Hintjens, 
Aleksandr Grishchenko, deputy head of the Russian diplomatic 
mission, and German Charge d'Affaires Claude Robert Elner 
informed President Tudjman about conclusions reached at a 
meeting in Geneva yesterday by ministers of foreign affairs of 
the countries whose diplomatic envoys make up the contact group 
for Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  They handed President Tudjman a letter which the ministers 
of 
the contact group had sent to Alija Izetbegovic, president of 
the Bosnia-Herzegovina presidency, Kresimir Zubak, 
representative of the Bosnian Croats, and Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic, containing the principles that the contact 
group is going to follow to halt the hostilities in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. President Tudjman said he agreed with these 
principles and promised to exert his influence so that the 
negotiating sides should accept these principles and new 
measures for the resolution of the Bosnia-Herzegovina crisis. 

</TEXT>

