<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assembly Committee Hails International Position </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Assembly Committee Hails International Position </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505122694 Zagreb VJESNIK in Serbo-Croatian 19 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU2505122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb VJESNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [HINA report: "Granic Is Not Going to Belgrade"] </F>
  [Text] Dr. Mate Granic, deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister of the Republic of Croatia, stated that Croatia would 
persist on the position that the international sanctions against 
the so-called FRY not be lifted or suspended unless the status 
of the UNPA's [UN Protected Areas] is resolved, and that he did 
not intend to go to Belgrade for the time being. 
  Minister Granic said this on 17 May, in the introductory 
speech at the session of the Foreign Policy Parliament 
Committee, at which he spoke about the present foreign political 
position of Croatia. Croatian ambassadors to the UN, the 
European Union, the CSCE, the Council of Europe, and Belgium, 
Germany, Turkey, Bosnia-Herzegovina, and Slovenia also 
participated in the Committee activities. 
  The main topics of the 15th Committee session, chaired by 
Dr. 
Zarko Domljan, were the international position of Croatia, the 
situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina after the Washington and Vienna 
agreements, and relations with the neighboring countries and 
international superpowers. 
  "Croatia has never been in a better international position 
than it is now," said Dr. Granic, adding that the procedure for 
accepting Croatia in the Council of Europe has been restarted, 
and that there have been announcements that economic 
arrangements with international financial institutions will be 
made. 
  Everybody present agreed that the main reasons for the 
improvement of the position of Croatia were the agreements 
between Croats and Bosniaks in Bosnia-Herzegovina, which, as Dr. 
Mario Nobilo, Croatian ambassador to the UN in New York, said, 
Croatia must strictly observe. He, like the other participants, 
said that Croatia is still in a very difficult position, and 
that the Bosniak- Croat federation is also a chance for Croatia 
to get closer to Europe. 
  Nobilo also emphasized the importance of the "clear and 
aggressive appearance" Croatia made before the international 
forces with the aim of changing the UNPROFOR mandate, and to 
channel the money spent on the "static preservation of the 
situation" in the UNPA's to financing the return of the refugees 
and the restoration of the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

