<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic Said To Reject EU Division Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Izetbegovic Said To Reject EU Division Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405132694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1105 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" report] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, May 24 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslem leader 
Alija Izetbegovic on Tuesday [24 May] dismissed as utterly 
unacceptable the European Union (E.U.) plan on the territorial 
division of the former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
under which 51 per cent of the territory would go to the 
Moslem-Croat federation, and 49 per cent to the Serbs. 
  In a statement to Radio France International (RFI), whose 
programme was monitored in Belgrade, Izetbegovic said that the 
world's insistence on such a settlement implied a continuation 
of the war. Foreign ministers of the United States, Russia, 
Great Britain and the European `troika' (Belgium, Greece and 
Germany) accepted in mid-May the E.U. formula envisaging this 
division of the Bosnian territory. 
  The Bosnian Serbs, who owned 64 per cent of the territory 
before the outbreak of the war in 1992, now control 70 per cent. 
Izetbegovic described the forthcoming Geneva meeting of a 
Bosnian Moslem delegation with U.S. presidential envoy Charles 
Redman and the contact group for Bosnia not as negotiations, but 
simply as meetings in which Redman and the contact group would 
inform the Bosnian Moslem side about their stands. 
  The contact group, made up of U.S., Russian, E.U. and U.N. 
representatives, was set up in late April with the aim of 
restoring the Bosnian peace process. Izetbegovic took another 
opportunity to disparage special U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi and 
said that Akashi had fallen into oblivion and that he was 
already regarded as history in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56001 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu101_i_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-101 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic Hails `Decisive' Aid From Iran </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic Hails `Decisive' Aid From Iran </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405091894 Tehran IRNA in English 0910 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405091894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 24, IRNA -- Foreign Ministry's special 
envoy to Bosnia Ebrahim Rahimpur called on the Bosnian Prime 
Minister Haris Silajdzic Monday [23 May] in Bosnia and exchanged 
views on current developments in that country. Rahimpur voiced 
Iran's readiness to continue its humanitarian aid to and 
diplomatic support for Muslim people of Bosnia. Meanwhile, 
Silajdzic lauded Islamic Republic of Iran for its relief 
supplies to Bosnian Muslims and added that Iran's aid have been 
decisive and considerable. 

</TEXT>

