<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croats, Muslims Coordinate Negotiations Stance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Croats, Muslims Coordinate Negotiations Stance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505162594 Zagreb VJESNIK in Serbo-Croatian 25 May 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> AU2505162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb VJESNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [HINA report on a statement by Kresimir Zubak, leader of the </F>
Bosnian Croat negotiating team, in Geneva; date not given: "`We 
Are Not Giving the Corridor to the Serbs'"] 
  [Text] "We have coordinated our positions with those of 
the Muslim delegation and established the starting points for 
the negotiations with the Serb side, but we do not expect that 
any significant progress will be made in the peace talks," said 
Kresimir Zubak, leader of the negotiation team of the Bosnian 
Croats, before the three-day peace talks between the delegations 
of the three warring sides and the members of the contact group 
for Bosnia- Herzegovina that, on the initiative of the United 
States, will be held beginning Tuesday evening behind closed 
door in Talloires, a French town near Geneva. 
  The Croat delegation, accompanied by the Croatian ambassador 
in Geneva, Dr. Miomir Zuzul, met with Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime 
Minister Haris Silajdzic on Tuesday morning in Geneva to 
establish a joint negotiating position regarding the territorial 
demarcation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Zubak said that the Croat and Bosniak delegations would 
support the maps established by the Vienna agreement, which 
anticipates 58 percent of the territory for the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina federation and 42 percent for the Bosnian 
Serbs. The Croat and Bosniak delegations are prepared to 
discuss the possibility of a compromise and the division of the 
territory into 51 and 49 percent, as stated in the European plan. 
  With regard to the so-called corridor, the position of the 
Croat and Bosniak delegations is that, in principle, the Serbs 
being given a corridor is out of the question, as the Croats and 
the Muslims would then also demand certain corridors going 
through Serb territories, said Zubak. However, he added, if the 
international community insists on this, there is a possibility 
of introducing free roads in Bosnia-Herzegovina, under UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Forces] control, in accordance with the solutions 
contained in the Vance-Owen plan. 
  As far as the talks on the future political and legal 
organization of Bosnia-Herzegovina are concerned, we are 
prepared to discuss all the possible solutions, including the 
Serb side joining the federation, or a loose Bosnia-Herzegovina 
union consisting of the Croat-Bosniak federation and the future 
Serb republic, as stated in the Vance-Owen plan, said Zubak. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56018 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu102aa_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-102 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations Meet With Contact Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegations Meet With Contact Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605003294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2301 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605003294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Talloires, May 25 (TANJUG) -- Foreign minister of 
the Bosnian Serb Republic Aleksa Buha said on Wednesday that the 
Bosnian Serb delegation told the contact group that a ceasefire 
must be established first in the former Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, and that the territorial delimitation would 
be resolved later. The contact group for Bosnia-Herzegovina 
began separate talks in the French tourist resort of Talloires, 
close to the Swiss border, on Wednesday with two delegations -- 
of Moslems and Croats and of the Bosnian Serbs. 
  The official platform for the talks is the Geneva 
declaration 
signed on May 13 by ministers of the United States, Russia and 
the European Union (E.U.), it was announced. Under this 
declaration, the warring sides in Bosnia-Herzegovina are urged 
to sign a four-month ceasefire, during which time they would 
agree on the division of the territory of former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina according to the E.U. formula of 49 percent 
for the Serbs and 51 percent for the Moslem-Croat federation. 
  In a statement to Bosnian Serb television, Buha said that 
the 
talks today had primarily focused on territorial delimitation. 
He said that the Bosnian Serb delegation had insisted that 
other criteria, in addition to the one of percentage of 
population, be also taken into consideration in the 
delimitation. These criteria include property, resources, and 
certainly, the one of functionality of the two future states in 
the territory of former Bosnia-Herzegovina -- the Moslem-Croat 
federation and the Serb Republic, he said. According to land 
registers, 64 percent of the land in Bosnia- Herzegovina is 
owned by Serbs. 
  "It is my impression that the members of the contact group 
are very interested in these arguments and I believe that, if 
they have not accepted them, then that they have seriously taken 
them into consideration. It remains to be seen what will come 
out in the end," Buha said. The contact group includes 
diplomats from the United States, Russia, Great Britain, France 
and Germany. 
  Buha said that the Bosnian Serb delegation had made it clear 
at the very beginning that it considered the international 
conference on former Yugoslavia as the valid body, and that the 
contact group could only be a place where views will be 
exchanged and possible new suggestions be made. The members of 
the contact group "have accepted such a role and they did not 
have any greater ambitions than to be part of the diplomatic 
process within the conference on former Yugoslavia," Buha said. 
  Representatives of Bosnian Moslems and Croats said upon 
arrival in Talloires that they would demand 58 percent of the 
territory of former Bosnia-Herzegovina for their federation, but 
foreign agencies reported that they had agreed later during the 
day to discuss the division of territory on the basis of 51 
percent for the Moslem-Croat federation and 49 percent for the 
Serb state. Bosnian Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic announced 
ahead of the talks in Talloires that the Moslem side would 
negotiate and wage war until it wins 58 percent of the territory 
of former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

