<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDS Faction Walks Out of National Assembly </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDS Faction Walks Out of National Assembly </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505134394 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1300 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2505134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Mariya Tsenkova from the National </F>
Assembly] 
  [Text] This is an Assembly session that will be decisive 
for the government. At the beginning of today's session Filip 
Dimitrov, leader of the Union of Democratic Forces [SDS], made a 
statement on behalf of his faction in which he asked Prime 
Minister Berov to resign. An attempt to repeat the 
no-confidence vote will be viewed by the SDS deputies as a 
violation of the Constitution. If this is allowed it will 
represent a danger for Bulgaria's democracy, Dimitrov said. 
  Replying to the statement, Velko Vulkanov of the Bulgarian 
Socialist Party [BSP] demanded that the 19 May vote on 
structural and personnel changes in the government be annulled, 
and asked National Assembly Chairman Aleksandur Yordanov to 
resign for what Vulkanov described as a violation of 
parliamentary practice. 
  BSL leader Zhan Videnov assured the hall -- the SDS deputies 
and Aleksandur Yordanov had already walked out -- that there 
will be a debate on the draft resolution proposed by the 
government on a framework agreement with parliament. 
  The political forces that support the cabinet are now 
holding 
consultations at the invitation of Prime Minister Berov, who 
still has not come to the National Assembly. It appears that 
the Movement for Rights and Freedoms [DPS] will participate in 
the consultations. The deputies of the New Alliance for 
Democracy [NSD] are divided. Part of them will probably 
participate in the consultations, while others demand separate 
talks with the prime minister. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56020 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu102_b_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-102 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berov Begins Consultations With Parties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berov Begins Consultations With Parties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505152794 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1400 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2505152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Mariya Tsenkova from the National </F>
Assembly] 
  [Text] The situation here continues to unfold. Prime 
Minister Lyuben Berov met in the parliament with Zhan Videnov, 
leader of the Bulgarian Socialist Party [BSP], and Ahmed Dogan, 
leader of the Movement for Rights and Freedoms [DPS]. After the 
meeting Dogan said that the DPS will support the framework 
agreement proposed by the government, if it is supported by at 
least four parliamentary factions. Dogan did not specify what 
factions precisely should support the agreement, but he does not 
exclude a situation in which the cabinet will have to resign. 
  According to Zhan Videnov, procedural issues were discussed 
at the meeting with Prime Minister Berov on consultations 
between the prime minister and the parliamentary factions. 
  Nora Ananieva said that real consultations are yet to be 
held, and it appears that precisely this is taking place at 
present at the National Assembly's West Hall, where the prime 
minister is meeting with BSP representatives and two 
representatives of the New Alliance for Democracy [NSD]. Mr. 
Oktay of the DPS entered the hall, saw what is happening there, 
left the hall, and refused to make any statements. 
  Dr. Yordan Todorov of the NSD said that he is attending the 
meeting as a representative of his faction, but the NSD will 
nevertheless insist on holding separate talks with the prime 
minister. 
  Deputy Ivan Pushkarov has not been offered the post of 
deputy 
prime minister. If signing an agreement is on the agenda, 
Pushkarov's people will not sign. It is not the business of the 
prime minister to make such moves, Pushkarov said. Several 
seconds ago Yunal Lyutfi of the DPS joined the meeting that is 
taking place at the National Assembly's West Hall. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

