<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic Presents Report on Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Granic Presents Report on Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505153294 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2505153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] International political and financial support to 
Croatia depends to a considerable extent on the implementation 
of the Washington agreement, Mate Granic, deputy prime minister 
and foreign minister, said today in the Parliament's House of 
Counties, where he presented his report on current Croatian 
foreign policy issues. [passage omitted] 
  Among other things, he stressed that extensive diplomatic 
activities were under way to simultaneously resolve the crisis 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina and reintegrate the UN protected areas 
into the Croatian legal system and to ensure that the sanctions 
against Serbia are linked to the progress in the talks on the UN 
pretected areas. He described the Vienna talks on the 
implementation of the Washington agreement as extremely 
important. He also mentioned, as he put it, good relations 
between Croatia and its neighboring European countries, and in 
particular with the United States, and went on to stress that 
the international political and financial support to Croatia 
depended to a considerable extent on the implementation of the 
Washington agreement. He said that the attempt to destabilize 
the Croatian parliament had somewhat affected Croatia's 
international position. 
  [Begin Granic recording] Foreign countries would certainly 
welcome a negotiated solution. The deepening of the crisis will 
certainly not benefit anyone and will be to the detriment of the 
Republic of Croatia. [end recording] 
  During the question time, Mate Granic said Croatia would 
definitely not extend the UN Protection Force's mandate unless 
it deployed its forces on Croatian borders with Serbia and 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to prevent armed provocations and ethnic 
cleansing. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

