<H3> <TI>   RSK Serbs Want Talks With Croatia in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSK Serbs Want Talks With Croatia in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505212494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2104 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505212494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, May 25 (TANJUG) -- The government of the 
republic of Serb Krajina (R.S.K.) remains by its stand that 
negotiations with Croatia should be held in Geneva, because this 
secures the R.S.K.'s equality in the negotiations, R.S.K. 
foreign minister Milan Babic has told TANJUG. 
  "By conditioning the venue for the negotiations, Croatia is 
trying to impose a political approach which does not comply 
either with the principles which we have advocated, or with the 
building up of mutual confidence founded on interest," Babic 
said on Wednesday, after an R.S.K. government session. He 
expressed regret that the deputy co-chairmen of the conference 
on former Yugoslavia had not yet found a compromise solution for 
overcoming this problem, but were holding out solely for 
proposals by the Croatian side. 
  The key to the final resolving of relations with Croatia is 
in the recognition of the R.S.K. by the international community 
and in the signing of a peace accord with Croatia on that basis, 
Babic said. 

</TEXT>

