<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Condemns Cairo Statement on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Condemns Cairo Statement on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505192194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1528 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, May 25 (TANJUG) -- The Foreign Ministry of 
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.) on Wednesday 
expressed its embitterment over Cairo's conduct and assessed 
Egypt's accusations that the F.R.Y. is accountable for the war 
in the former Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina as 
"senseless and irresponsible". Egyptian Foreign Minister 'Amr 
Musa on Tuesday said Egypt would not invite the F.R.Y. to take 
part in a conference of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) to be 
held in Cairo from May 31 to June 3, stating without any 
arguments a series of shocking accusations about the F.R.Y.'s 
alleged involvement in the civil war in neighbouring 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  "The Egyptian foreign minister's statement is unacceptable 
and does not comply with the actual state of affairs," officials 
of the F.R.Y. Foreign Ministry told TANJUG. "His explanation 
and arguments have been long surmounted, not only by reality and 
truth which is pushing its way despite the media campaign 
against the F.R.Y., but also by the events such as a ministerial 
meeting of Russia, the European Union and the U.S. on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina in Geneva on May 13," the same sources said. 
  The F.R.Y. Foreign Ministry set out that it interpreted 
Egypt's decision as a gross violation of the agreement on the 
F.R.Y.'s participation in the NAM meetings when crisis in the 
former Yugoslavia is discussed and as a misuse of the role of 
the host at the NAM ministerial meetings. 
  "We interpret that decision as a wish to have the NAM openly 
sided with the Moslems in the civil war in Bosnia," it was said 
in the F.R.Y. Foreign Ministry. After the NAM summit in 
Jakarta, a so called gentlemen's agreement was drawn up under 
which the F.R.Y. has a full right to actively participate in the 
NAM meetings, at which either the crisis in the former 
Yugoslavia or other topics are being discussed. 
  Egypt defaulted regarding the New York agreement and acted 
in 
an ungentlemanlike way. An obvious intention is to exclude the 
F.R.Y. from the NAM, but this would require a full consensus. 
The Islamic bloc in the NAM is trying to persuade, first of all 
the non-aligned countries of the black Africa to join the bloc 
of the "friends" of the Bosnian Moslems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

