<H3> <TI>   Minority Rights Minister Meets Hungarian Envoy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minority Rights Minister Meets Hungarian Envoy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505162794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1112 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 25 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Human and 
Minority Rights Minister Margit Savovic, who has met with the 
charge d'affaires at the Hungarian Embassy in Belgrade, Andras 
Vincze, hailed the Hungarian proposal that the two countries' 
experts meet to exchange experiences on the resolution of the 
status of their national minorities. Savovic informed Vincze 
about the comprehensive preparation of a federal law on 
minorities in Yugoslavia, the Federal Information Ministry 
announced. 
  The two officials also discussed the effects of the 
international sanctions on the living conditions and health of 
the Yugoslavs and the problems in ferrying humanitarian aid via 
Hungary. Vincze said that Hungary, as a member of the United 
Nations, is obliged to honour its decisions, but is doing 
everything possible to facilitate the transport of relief aid to 
Yugoslavia. He said that last year 12,000 trucks carrying 
humanitarian aid had passed through Hungary, and that there had 
been problems only in four-five cases due to a lack of adequate 
documentation. 

</TEXT>

