<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy Trip Cancellation Explained </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovskiy Trip Cancellation Explained </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505183394 Bratislava SME in Slovak 20 May 94 pp 1, 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU2505183394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SME </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ivan Drabek: "Vladimir Zhirinovskiy Will Not Come </F>
to Slovakia"] 
  [Excerpts] Bratislava/Moscow -- [passage omitted] 
Grigoriy Serebrennikov, press secretary of the Liberal 
Democratic Party of Russia [LDP] parliamentary group, informed 
SME by telephone about the circumstances of the sudden change in 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's program. According to Serebrennikov, 
Zhirinovskiy intends radically to limit his trips abroad in the 
future. The LDP leader decided not to travel to Slovakia under 
the impression of his visit to Saratov on Wednesday [18 May] 
where, according to Serebrennikov, he saw with his own eyes the 
dramatic situation the country finds itself in. "Factories are 
standing still, people have not received any wages since 
January, a social explosion is looming. Vladimir Volfovich 
reached the conclusion that his task is now to tour Russian 
cities and to talk to the people there so that, when the 
situation comes to a head tomorrow, they are able to orient 
themselves and seek a solution in support of the LDP," 
Serebrennikov said. According to the LDP press secretary, the 
trip to Slovakia has not been postponed but canceled. In the 
foreseeable future, there will not be a single opening in 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's busy schedule. [passage omitted] 
  [Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak on 20 May on pages 1 and 2 
carries a 500-word Vladimir Jancura, Boris Latta report, 
entitled "Visit Postponed Again," which provides a different 
explanation for the cancellation of Zhirinovskiy's visit to 
Slovakia. According to the report, Bratislava lawyer Jozef 
Lauko, who describes himself as "Zhirinovskiy's friend of long 
standing," told the PRAVDA reporters that three members of 
Zhirinovskiy's entourage "had problems with their travel 
documents. It seems that the 'AB-Sluzhebnaya' stamp, 
identifying holders of official passports, was missing in them." 
Lauko voices the assumption that the three men in question were 
Zhirinovskiy's personal bodyguards and that "for understandable 
reasons, the party leadership did not permit Mr. Zhirinovskiy to 
travel without bodyguards."] 

</TEXT>

