<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim Attacks on Serbs Reported in North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslim Attacks on Serbs Reported in North </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605000794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2339 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605000794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Doboj, May 25 (TANJUG) -- Moslem forces on Wednesday 
[25 March] continued attacking Serb settlements and army 
positions in the northern part of the former Yugoslav republic 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina, which was also confirmed by the United 
Nations Protection Force. The most intensive Moslem fire, from 
all available infantry and artillery weapons, was reported on 
the Teslic front, Bosnian Serb Army sources said. Serb Army 
units were forced to return fire in order to protect lives and 
positions. 
  Moslem forces fired 11 shells on Teslic itself but the 
attack 
fortunately caused only damage to local facilities without any 
casualties. On the southern part of the Teslic battlefront, a 
large Moslem terrorist group was sent to penetrate deep into the 
Serb territory and carry out silent liquidation of Serb 
civilians and other terrorist actions, Bosnian Serb Army sources 
said, adding that the group had suffered a heavy defeat after 
walking into a mine field. 
  The group left behind much of their equipment while trying 
to 
escape and take the wounded with them. On the Ozren battlefront 
south of Doboj, Moslem forces opened infantry and sniper fire on 
Serb settlements and, after massing troops in the vicinity of 
Serb defence lines on the south-western part of the front, made 
frequent and violent reconnaissance missions, said Serb Army 
sources. 
  Bosnian Serb Army units were forced to return fire and 
prevent this kind of activity, they said. On the southern part 
of the Vozuca battlefront, Moslem forces opened strong artillery 
fire on Serb positions after bringing in fresh troops. The Serb 
Army returned fire, it was announced. 
  Moslem assaults were also reported on the Trebava front. 
  Moslem and Croat forces in northern Bosnia-Herzegovina are 
preparing an offensive whose aim is to cut the land corridor 
linking the eastern and western parts of the Bosnian Serb 
Republic. 

</TEXT>

