<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Observes Continued Army Offensive </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Observes Continued Army Offensive </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505123094 Paris AFP in English 1200 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2505123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, May 25 (AFP) -- Moslem-led Bosnian 
Government forces Wednesday [25 May] pressed on for the second 
day an offensive against Serbs west of Tesanj, in the north of 
the country, the UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR] said here. 
[passage omitted] On the ground, EC observers reported that 
Tuesday's fighting, which involved artillery exchanges, left at 
least three dead among government forces and nine among 
civilians, according to Major Rob Annink, spokesman for 
UNPROFOR. Annink also pointed to the presence of three tanks, 
two of them Soviet model T-84s, in government lines, the first 
time they had been noticed in the region. He was unable to say 
whether the tanks were part of the Bosnian Army's armor or 
whether they had been borrowed from local HVO [Croatian Defense 
Council] Croat forces, now their nominal allies. 
  The Bosnian forces were pushing westwards, towards the 
Serb-held town of Teslic, possibly in order to seize some 
strategic heights and so bolster their defensive positions, 
Annink said. The government attack was a "limited" one, but was 
"well prepared and continuing," he said. 
  Further north, calm returned to the outskirts of the 
Serb-held town of Brcko, an area linking western Bosnia to 
Serbia. On Monday, government forces fired 10 shells at the 
town, five of which hit a power transformer, Annink said. 
Elsewhere in the country, there were clashes in the Bugojno and 
Turbe regions of central Bosnia and near Kladanj and Dastansko, 
northeast of here. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

