<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Assume Federal Duties Temporarily </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Assume Federal Duties Temporarily </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505195394 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2505195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Bosnia-Herzegovina Government at today's 
session, which was chaired by Deputy Prime Minister Edib Bukvic, 
passed the [word indistinct] Law on the Government of the 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, the Law on Ministries and Other 
Offices of the State Administration, the Law on the Government 
of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation, and the Law on Ministries 
and State Administration Offices of the Federation. 
  Until a final peace agreement for Bosnia-Herzegovina is 
reached, the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government will perform the role 
of the government of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation. The 
government will consist of a prime minister, a deputy prime 
minister, 11 ministers to oversee ministries, and four ministers 
without portfolio. The deputy prime minister will also act as 
the defense minister. The ministers in charge of ministries 
must ensure that their deputies do not come from the same 
constituent ethnic group as them. 
  The Ministry for Special Purposes Production, the Ministry 
of 
Economy, the Ministry of Reconstruction and Development, the 
Ministry of Environment, the Ministry of Transport and 
Communication, the Ministry of Trade, and the Ministry of 
Information will cease to exist. 
  Based on the Bosnia-Herzegovina Constitution, the internal 
structure of the territory with a majority Bosniak and Croatian 
population in the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina has been 
transformed and a segment of the executive functions of the 
federation allocated to the government of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Federation. The ministries of the federation are: the Defense 
Ministry; the Ministry of Internal Affairs; the Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs; the Ministry of Finance; the Ministry of 
Justice; the Ministry of Energy and Industry; the Ministry of 
Transport and Communications; the Ministry of Urbanism, 
Resources, and Protection of Environment; the Ministry of Trade; 
the Ministry of Refugees and Social Policy; the Ministry of 
Health; and the Ministry of Education, Science and Culture. 
  The Bosnia-Herzegovina Government also passed a draft law on 
the Official Gazette of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

