<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims, Croats May Retreat on Land Demand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims, Croats May Retreat on Land Demand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605191694 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1730 
GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2605191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The talks the between international mediators 
and the three warring sides in Bosnia-Herzegovina ended in the 
French town of Talloires today. No agreement on the future of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina was reached. Journalists were banned from 
the talks venue, and the representatives of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina sides refused to comment. REUTERS reports 
that the Muslim, Serb, and Croat representatives are ready to 
resume talks in France or in Geneva within seven to 10 days. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] It is becoming obvious that the 
secret peace talks were only testing grounds for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina's warring sides; a preliminary exchange of 
opinions with the members of the Contact Group who are trying, 
as they stress, to complete their peace-building task in a 
professional and efficient way. [passage omitted] 
  The unity between the Croat and Bosniak delegations was 
noticeable during the talks. They presented good arguments to 
advocate the principles of the Washington and Vienna Agreements. 
In the name of a lasting peace Bosnian Croat leader Kresimir 
Zubak and Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic 
announced a possible retreat from the initial negotiating 
positions of 58 percent for the federation. However, the Serbs 
do not consider the percentage as the most important element. 
They are requesting richer and better quality territories. 
  The maps and haggling over the territorial division 
certainly 
dominated the talks. However, all combinations are still 
possible. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

