<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rose, Izetbegovic Discuss Gorazde Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rose, Izetbegovic Discuss Gorazde Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2605163694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 Gmt 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2605163694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Last night, General Michael Rose, commander of the 
UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] in Bosnia-Herzegovina, held 
talks with President of the Presidency Alija Izetbegovic on the 
implementation of the cease-fire and the deployment of peace 
forces on the east bank of the Drina River near Gorazde. This 
was announced today at the UNPROFOR command in Sarajevo. 
  General Rose proposed that Bosnia-Herzegovina Army units 
should withdraw from the east bank of the Drina River and that 
UNPROFOR units should be deployed in their place to protect 
Gorazde and maintain the cease-fire. On the basis of UN 
Security Council Resolution 913 and the NATO ultimatum, 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army units are not obliged to withdraw from 
either this part of town or the 3-km exclusion zone around 
Gorazde. UNPROFOR representative Major Annink said that the 
NATO ultimatum was still in force. We [words indistinct] the 
situation realistically and we are trying to solve the problem 
in Gorazde through negotiations, said Major Annink today. He 
added that General Rose yesterday attempted to talk to the 
aggressor's leader Radovan Karadzic, but that he had not 
succeeded in this. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

