<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rose Pays `Extremely Short' Visit to Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rose Pays `Extremely Short' Visit to Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2705111694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1000 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2705111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Enes Musovic from Gorazde] </F>
  [Excerpt] The long-awaited visit by General Michael Rose, 
commander of the UN forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina, to Gorazde 
yesterday lasted only 20 minutes. During that extremely short 
time General Rose spoke with (Ferid Buljubasic), commander of 
the Eastern Bosnia Operative Group of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army in Gorazde. The issues touched upon in this blitz 
conversation were the cooperation of the military authorities in 
Gorazde with the units of the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR], 
and the problems connected with the implementation of the UN 
Security Council Resolution 913. 
  The general returned to Sarajevo with his associates, while 
the people of Gorazde remain in the same situation as prior to 
his visit. The aggressor's soldiers, dressed in uniforms of 
so-called Serbian police, yesterday afternoon inflicted severe 
wounds on a 10-year-old boy in the city district of Bare with a 
M-84 machine gun. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

