<H3> <TI>   Democratic Union `Not Contemplating Coalition' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Democratic Union `Not Contemplating Coalition' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605171294 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 0500 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2605171294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 0500 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Representatives of rightwing forces in Slovakia held 
their third meeting last night, following the parliament 
session. Their one-hour discussion focused on the possibility of 
forming a strong rightwing election bloc. According to Jan 
Carnogursky, the Christian Democratic Movement [KDH] is 
skeptical in that respect. That is what he briefly told me about 
the bloc, which is also represented by the National Democratic 
Party, the Democratic Union, the Democratic Party, and the Party 
of Businessmen and Tradesmen. 
  [Begin recording] [Carnogursky] If all of us wanted to form 
one election bloc, then according to the Elections Law, it would 
mean that we would have to win at least 10 percent of the vote 
in order to actually make it into the parliament. For that 
reason, we have simply continued pursuing our idea of getting 
rightwing deputies to the Slovak parliament. That trend will 
continue until 10 June. Thereafter, the party ticket will be 
complete because extending the process of forming election blocs 
and negotiating after 10 June would be wasteful. 
  [Reporter] Mr. Cernak [National Democratic Party chairman] 
said he will not form any election coalition without you, the 
KDH. What is the situation with regard to the Democratic Union, 
the party headed by a chairman who enjoys the greatest 
popularity of around 20 percent? What is the Democratic Union's 
reaction? 
  [Carnogursky] The Democratic Union intends to go into the 
elections alone and it is not contemplating a coalition with any 
other party. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

