<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indian President Arrives, Meets With Zhelev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Indian President Arrives, Meets With Zhelev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2705060394 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2705060394 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] India and Bulgaria have signed six agreements for 
promoting cooperation in various fields. The agreements were 
signed in Sofia yesterday on the first day of the state visit of 
the president, Dr. Shankar Dayal Sharma, to Bulgaria. An 
important agreement signed by the two countries relates to 
cooperation in combating international terrorism and illegal 
trafficking in narcotic drugs. The home minister, Mr. S.B. 
Chavan, signed the agreement on behalf of India. The other 
agreements relate to cooperation in tourism, avoidance of double 
taxation and for cooperation in plant protection measures and in 
veterinary and sanitation areas. Earlier, the president, Dr. 
Sharma, had talks with the Bulgarian president, Dr. Zhelyu 
Zhelev. The talks later continued at delegation levels. 
  The Bulgarian president supported India's stand on Kashmir 
and urged New Delhi and Islamabad to resolve the issue through 
bilateral talks under the Simla Agreement. An official 
spokesman said Dr. Sharma appreciated Bulgaria's consistent 
support to issues of concern to India. The two leaders also 
discussed bilateral issues and matters of regional importance. 
  Speaking at a banquet hosted in his honor by the Bulgarian 
president, Dr. Sharma underlined the need for closer economic 
cooperation between the two countries. He said the changes 
which have taken place in both the countries have opened up 
fresh avenues of cooperation and urged entrepreneurs to take 
full advantage of the emerging markets. He said the 
Indo-Bulgarian friendship is motivated by the desire to work for 
a peaceful world and harmonious humanity. 

</TEXT>

