<H3> <TI>   Baudys Reacts to Comments on Army Discipline </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Baudys Reacts to Comments on Army Discipline </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2605203394 Prague CTK in English 1609 GMT 26 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2605203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 26 (CTK) -- The Czech Army Command is 
not trying to gloss over slack Army discipline, Czech Defense 
Minister Antonin Baudys said in a statement today, responding to 
a deputy. A blueprint for tightening Army discipline would be 
ready by June 30, Baudys says in the statement. 
  Fifty-six percent of offenses committed by ordinary soldiers 
break military codes, the statement reads, listing desertion, 
disregard of the leave deadline, bullying and non-observance of 
patrol and supervision duties as the most common violations. 
  The overall state of society is the most powerful single 
factor influencing army discipline, Baudys says. Some blame 
lies with officers and staffs but it is mostly non-commissioned 
officers who have low standards of behavior and work, setting 
the privates a bad example and even inciting trouble. 
  The standards of common soldiers worsen over the time 
served. 
The longer-serving soldiers have a negative attitude to service, 
Baudys says. Broad measures involving civilian consulting 
bodies will have to be adopted to stamp out bullying, the 
statement reads. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56132 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu103__a94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-103-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duray on `Distressing' Government Attitudes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duray on `Distressing' Government Attitudes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405165794 Prague CTK in English 1446 GMT 24 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2405165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava May 24 (CTK) -- Egyutteles Party 
Chairman Miklos Duray said he had discussed the need to solve 
the bilateral relations of post-communist countries with the 
government but found its attitude to the problem no less 
"distressing" than the previous government. 
  "We will make one last attempt in the framework of the 
coalition," Duray said at a press conference today. If they are 
unsuccessful the party will probably issue a statement asking 
the international community to take account of their requests, 
he said. Egyutteles is the largest party in Slovakia, 
representing the half a million members of the Hungarian 
minority. 
  In Duray's view, the stability pact, proposed by French 
Prime 
Minister Edouard Balladur, should also resolve the problems of 
minorities. Bilateral agreements with neighbouring countries 
should address the problem and legitimate representatives of 
minorities should participate in the negotiations, he said. The 
status of minorities should be defined in a definitive bilateral 
agreement, such as exists between Austria and Italy in the case 
of the South Tyrolean minority. 
  The Hungarian politicians are requesting that Bratislava 
grant collective rights to the Hungarian community in Slovakia 
but the government refuses, preferring that individual rights be 
accorded to them as to all other citizens. 
  The stability pact envisages the signing of bilateral 
agreements between countries, but this aspect has been rejected 
by certain politicians in Slovakia and Romania, Duray said. 
  The pact is an elaboration of the original Balladur plan of 
last September, and stems from Western fears that the tragedy of 
Yugoslavia may be repeated in other countries of the former 
communist bloc. It is designed to prevent international 
disputes over national minorities and joint borders. European 
countries begin to debate the adoption of the pact in Paris on 
Thursday [26 May]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

