<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec's Expectations for Paris Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zieleniec's Expectations for Paris Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505205394 Prague CTK in English 1813 GMT 25 may 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2505205394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 25 (CTK) -- Czech Foreign Minister 
Josef Zieleniec said today that a two-day conference on the 
stability pact, which opens in Paris tomorrow, will be the 
culmination of many months of effort by diplomats from France 
and the countries applying for European Union (EU) membership. 
  He told reporters prior to his departure for Paris that he 
hoped that the conference would start a process "leading to 
greater understanding between the states in central and Eastern 
Europe, and also in their relation to the EU." Zieleniec said 
he did not expect any document to be signed in Paris, as the 
conference, he said, would rather be a political event. 
Zieleniec expressed satisfaction with all the texts prepared 
for the conference, as they now reflect consensus in France, the 
EU but also in the associated countries. 
  The stability pact will not lead to the creation of new 
international institutions, but will start a process which will 
(naturally) become part of the Conference on Security and 
Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) process, Zieleniec said. 

</TEXT>

